Task1

fit <- lm(Gasfurn$dependent ~ Gasfurn$independent, data = Gasfurn)

acf(residuals(fit))

Ans1 - It appears that there is significant correlation in the residuals upto the 4th lag. This violates of the assumption of independence in the linear regression model.

Task2

resid<-residuals(fit)

arima_resid <- arima(resid, order = c(0, 0, 1))

adj_gas <- Gasfurn$dependent- arima_resid$coef[1] * resid

fit_adj <- lm(adj_gas ~ Gasfurn$independent, data = Gasfurn)


plot(residuals(fit_adj), type = "l", main = "Residuals of Adjusted Linear Regression Model")

Task3

Task8

# Durbin-Watson tests
dwtest1 = sum((arima_resid$residuals - stats::lag(arima_resid$residuals))^2, na.rm = TRUE) /
       sum(arima_resid$residuals^2, na.rm = TRUE)
dwtest2 = sum((arima_resid2$residuals - stats::lag(arima_resid2$residuals))^2, na.rm = TRUE) /
       sum(arima_resid2$residuals^2, na.rm = TRUE)
dwtest3 = sum((arima_resid3$residuals - stats::lag(arima_resid3$residuals))^2, na.rm = TRUE) /
       sum(arima_resid3$residuals^2, na.rm = TRUE)
dwtest4 = sum((arima_resid4$residuals - stats::lag(arima_resid4$residuals))^2, na.rm = TRUE) /
       sum(arima_resid4$residuals^2, na.rm = TRUE)
dwtest5 = sum((arima_resid5$residuals - stats::lag(arima_resid5$residuals))^2, na.rm = TRUE) /
       sum(arima_resid5$residuals^2, na.rm = TRUE)
dwtest6 = sum((arfima_model$resid - stats::lag(arfima_model$resid))^2, na.rm = TRUE) /
       sum(arfima_model$resid^2, na.rm = TRUE)

Task10.1

library(lmtest)
library(forecast)

# Load the data (replace with your own data)

y <- residuals(lm(Gasfurn$dependent ~ Gasfurn$independent))

# Bootstrap residuals
set.seed(123)
nboot <- 500
boot_resids <- bld.mbb.bootstrap(y, nboot)
boot_resids<-as.matrix(boot_resids)
estimate_arima <- function(x) {
  x <- as.numeric(x)  # ensure input is numeric
  if (length(x) < 3) {
    return(c(ar=NA, ma=NA))  # return NA coefficients for short series
  }
  tryCatch({
    model <- Arima(x, order=c(1,0,1), include.mean=FALSE)
    return(c(ar=model$coef[1], ma=model$coef[2]))
  }, error = function(e) {
    return(c(ar=NA, ma=NA))
  })
}


ar_coeffs <- ma_coeffs <- rep(NA, nboot)
for (i in 1:nboot) {
  resids_i <- as.numeric(boot_resids[[i]])
  coeffs <- estimate_arima(resids_i)
  ar_coeffs[i] <- coeffs["ar.ar1"]
  ma_coeffs[i] <- coeffs["ma.ma1"]
}

# Plot the coefficient distributions
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
hist(ar_coeffs)
hist(ma_coeffs)

Ans10.1 - The coefficient distributions for autoregression and moving averages are close to the standard normal distribution. This is because the sample size is large (500 iterations) and the underlying data generating process is well-behaved. ARIMA(1,0,1) model assumes that the residuals are normally distributed.

Task10.2

ar_ci <- quantile(ar_coeffs, c(0.025, 0.975))
cat("95% Confidence interval for AR coefficient:", ar_ci, "\n")
## 95% Confidence interval for AR coefficient: 0.9123613 0.9258276
ma_ci <- quantile(ma_coeffs, c(0.025, 0.975))
